An antibody is an important protein in the immune system. It is created by the body in response to the presence of a foreign antigen.
The antibody center is a flexible region that can have different antigen binding sites.
Enhanced Blue Fluorescent Protein (EBFP) is a protein that emits Blue fluorescence when eXPosed to the 440-450 nm light wavelength range.

Coil-Ser is an artificial protein created from a Leucine zipper.
Enhanced Cyan Fluorescent Protein (ECFP) is a protein that emits cyan fluorescence when eXPosed to the 450-510 nm light wavelength range.
Repaired DNA is the result of Photolyase binding to damaged DNA created from UV light eXPosure.
The antibody head (The Fragment Antigen Binding region - FAB region) is the region of the antibody that contains the antigen binding site, allowing for the antibody to bind to the foreign substance.
The Head and Neck are the components that allow Kinesin to -walk- along microtubules.
A kinesin is a motor protein that carries cell cargo, also known as vesicles, throughout the cell along microtubules.
Leucine Zipper is a special structure that forms a dimer between alpha helices. They contain an abundance of Leucines in periodic order that interlay like a zipper.
mCherry is a protein that emits red fluorescence when eXPosed to the 590-600 nm light wavelength range.
mOrange is a protein that emits orange fluorescence when eXPosed to the 565-575 nm light wavelength range.
Alpha-tubulin and Beta-tubulin form a complex which is the main building block for microtubules.
Enhanced Yellow Fluorescent Protein (EYFP) is a mutant of GFP that exhibits yellow fluorescence when in the 514 nm-527 nm light wavelength range.
Alpha Helices are polypeptide secondary structures that are the components of several proteins, ranging from hemoglobin to insulin.
Alpha-tubulin is one of the two major components that make up microtubules.

The Antigen-Binding site allows the antibody to recognize the specific antigen and bind to it accordingly. Antibodies are specific to certain antigens, meaning that the antigen binding site is different among all antibodies.

The Damaged DNA is a result of UV light eXPosure. This specific damaged DNA contains a Thymine Dimer. This can result in melanoma.
Flavin Adenine Dinucleotide (FAD) is a molecule within Photolyase that repairs the Thymine Dimer.
The antibody stalk (Fragment Crystallizable region - FC region) is the tail region of an antibody that allows white blood cells to identify and kill the foreign substance.

The Hinge is located in between the FAB and FC region of the antibody, which connects the two regions and allows for flexibility of the antibody.
